This just prevents all the null-checks and makes it easier to read.

@singingwolfboy With the API, the first time a draft is `POST`ed it will return a version of 0 (and no version needs to be passed in to this `POST`). Later, if a PUT request is made on that draft, you must pass `"version": 0`. The json response of the updated draft will include `"version": 1`.

Since it looks like the `create()` method only creates a local copy of the object and doesn't actually make an API request until `save()` is called it, then after the first `save()` the draft version returned should be 0 according to the logic above.

Could you change the other draft saves to be `update()` instead to be a little more explicit please, and make sure the draft version is 0 after the first save?

I'm wondering if directly linking those two is desirable, and I'm thinking it's not (I thought you also had some concerns about this when we first talked about it).  The vocab namespace is something that you shouldn't have to think about at all except for rare edge cases, but you have to if these are linked.  If we instead just have arbitrary keys, it's really easy to make sure they match up in the configuration file:

```json
{
  "token_indexers": {
    "words": "single_token",
    "characters": "token_characters",
  },
  ...
  "token embedder": {
    "words": "single_token_embedding",
    "characters": {
      "type": "cnn"
    }
  }
}
```

(some details missing, but I think you get the idea)

If you don't use a dictionary to do this, the keys that a token embedder should look for look like magic.

