```

Or Just inline a duplication of the `wait` function from our `Service` class with a comment/issue to remove the duplication at some point.

This works fine, but a more efficient way would be `return 301 https://$host$uri;`. That avoids firing up the comparatively expensive regex machinery (and, for my reference, has been supported since 0.7.51, released in 2009).

We might be able to do even better in the future if we make a fresh vhost for the HTTP side:
```
server {
    server_name example.com;
    return 301 https://$host$request_uri;
}
```
That eliminates even the `if` but would require a bit of redesign.

This definitely highlights that the code hasn't been run through here. We can test `handleFormattableMessages` and `createSourceUpdateAction` (with `replace` set) in another PR.

However, this does make me notice something we can abstract (if you feel like it) -- we can provide a helper that binds the id as the first argument (or you can bind it directly):

```js
function bindById(id, func) {
  return func.bind(null, id);
}
```

Then we can `.map(bindById(id, updateCellSource))`.

However, you could also:

```js
return setInputStream.filter(x => x.replace)
  .pluck('text')
  .map(updateCellSource.bind(null, id));
```

and not worry about a helper (we don't really need it).
